    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">But before we look at the code, let’s go through the very basics of neural networks.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Neurons and synapses</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The first building block of a neural network is, well, <a href="https://medium.com/learning-new-stuff/how-to-learn-neural-networks-758b78f2736e" target="_self">neurons</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A neuron is like a function, it takes a few inputs and returns an output.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">There are many different types of neurons. Our network is going to use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_function" target="_self">sigmoid neurons,</a> which take any given number and squash it to a value between <code>0</code> and <code>1</code>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The circle below illustrates a sigmoid neuron. Its input is <code>5</code> and its output is <code>1</code>. The arrows are called synapses, which connects the neuron to other layers in the network.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*TGn24UaXx1LNcyuiySa0NQ.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So <strong>why</strong> is the red number <code>5</code>? Because it’s the sum of the three synapses that’s connecting to the neuron as shown by the three arrows at the left. Let’s unpack that.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">At the far left we see two values plus a so called <strong>bias</strong> value. The values are <code>1</code> and <code>0</code> which are the green numbers. The bias value is <code>-2</code> which is the brown number.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">First, the two inputs are multiplied with their <strong>weights</strong>, which are <code>7</code> and <code>3</code> as shown by the blue numbers.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Finally we add it up with the bias and end up with <code>5</code> or the red number. This is the input for our artificial neuron.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*CjCW6wYx4zYF_X6OnaDCNQ.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As this is a sigmoid neuron which squashes any value to between 0 and 1, the output gets squeezed down to <code>1</code>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you connect a network of these neurons together, you have a neural network. This propagates forward from input to output, via neurons which are connected to each other through synapses. Like on the image below:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:46%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 350px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/format:webp/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 700w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 350px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png 700w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/350/1*9dt933ts_01LH25ERAM8mw.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The goal of a neural network is to train it to do generalizations, such as recognize hand written digits or email spam. And being a good at generalizing is a matter of having the right <strong>weights</strong> and <strong>bias</strong> values across the network. Like with the blue and brown numbers in our example above.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">When training the network, you’re simply showing it loads of examples such as hand written digits, and getting the network to predict the right answer.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">After each prediction, you’ll calculate <strong>how wrong</strong><em> </em>the prediction was, and adjust the weights and bias values so that the network will guess a little bit more correct the next time around. This learning process is called <mark>backpropagation</mark>. Do this thousands of times and your network will soon become good at generalizing.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">How backpropagation works technically is outside the scope of this tutorial, but here’s the three best sources I’ve found for understanding it:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><a href="http://mattmazur.com/2015/03/17/a-step-by-step-backpropagation-example/" target="_self">A Step by Step Backpropagation Example</a> — by <a style="color:green" href="https://medium.com/u/f481b80ce964?source=post_page-----343dafc50d49--------------------------------" target="_self">Matt Mazur</a></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><a href="http://karpathy.github.io/neuralnets/" target="_self">Hackers Guide to Neural Nets</a> — by <a style="color:green" href="https://medium.com/u/ac9d9a35533e?source=post_page-----343dafc50d49--------------------------------" target="_self">Andrej Karpathy</a></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><a href="http://neuralnetworksanddeeplearning.com/chap1.html" target="_self">NeuralNetworksAndDeepLarning</a> — by <a href="https://twitter.com/michael_nielsen" target="_self">Michael Nielsen</a></li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">The code</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now that you’ve gotten a basic intro, let’s jump into the code. The first thing we need to do is to create the layers. We do this with the <code>new Layer()</code> function in synaptic. The number passed to the function dictates how many neurons each layer should have.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you’re confused of what a <strong>layer</strong> is, check out the <a href="https://scrimba.com/casts/cast-1980" target="_self">screencast</a> above.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="iframe"><pre><span>const { Layer, Network } = window.synaptic;</span><span>var inputLayer = new Layer(2);<br/>var hiddenLayer = new Layer(3);<br/>var outputLayer = new Layer(1);</span></pre></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Next up we’ll connect these layers together and instantiate a new network, like this:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="iframe"><pre><span>inputLayer.project(hiddenLayer);<br/>hiddenLayer.project(outputLayer);</span><span>var myNetwork = new Network({<br/> input: inputLayer,<br/> hidden: [hiddenLayer],<br/> output: outputLayer<br/>});</span></pre></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So this is a 2–3–1 network, which can be visualized like this:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*IjY3wFF24sK9UhiOlf36Bw.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now let’s train the network:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="iframe"><pre><span>// train the network - learn XOR</span><span>var learningRate = .3;</span><span>for (var i = 0; i &lt; 20000; i++) {<br/>  // 0,0 =&gt; 0<br/>  myNetwork.activate([0,0]);<br/>  myNetwork.propagate(learningRate, [0]);</span><span>  // 0,1 =&gt; 1<br/>  myNetwork.activate([0,1]);<br/>  myNetwork.propagate(learningRate, [1]);</span><span>  // 1,0 =&gt; 1<br/>  myNetwork.activate([1,0]);<br/>  myNetwork.propagate(learningRate, [1]);</span><span>  // 1,1 =&gt; 0<br/>  myNetwork.activate([1,1]);<br/>  myNetwork.propagate(learningRate, [0]);<br/>}</span></pre></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Here we’re running the network 20,000 times. Each time we propagate forward and backwards four times, passing in the four possible inputs for this network: <code>[0,0] [0,1] [1,0] [1,1]</code> .</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We start by doing <code>myNetwork.activate([0,0])</code> , where <code>[0,0]</code> is the data point we’re sending into the network. This is the forward propagation, also called <strong>activating</strong><em> </em>the network. After each forward propagation we need to do a backpropagation, where the network updates it’s own weights and biases.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The backpropagation is done with this line of code: <code>myNetwork.propagate(learningRate, [0])</code>, where the <code>learningRate</code> is a constant that tells the network how much it should adjust its<strong> </strong>weights each time. The second parameter <code>0</code> represents the correct output given the input <code>[0,0]</code>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>The network then compares its own prediction to the correct label. This tells it how right or wrong it was.</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">It uses the comparison as a basis for correcting it’s own weights and bias values, so that it will guess a little bit more correct the next time.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">After it has done this process 20,000 times, we can check how well our network has learned by activating the network with all four possible inputs:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
